# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: predictive-maintenance-iiot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Most CM technologies are being standardized by ISO and ASTM.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Rotating equipment is an industry umbrella term that includes gearboxes, reciprocating and centrifugal machinery.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] The most commonly used method for rotating machines is vibration analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] The level of vibration can be compared with historical baseline values such as former start ups and shutdowns, and in some cases established standards such as load changes, to assess the severity.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Machinery and parts OEM also define vibration limits based on the machine design or of the internal parts, e.g. fault frequencies of bearings.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Interpreting the vibration signal obtained is an elaborate procedure that requires specialized training and experience.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] It is simplified by the use of state-of-the-art technologies that provide the vast majority of data analysis automatically and provide information instead of raw data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] One commonly employed technique is to examine the individual frequencies present in the signal.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] These frequencies correspond to certain mechanical components (for example, the various pieces that make up a rolling-element bearing) or certain malfunctions (such as shaft unbalance or misalignment).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] By examining these frequencies and their harmonics, the CM specialist can often identify the location and type of problem, and sometimes the root cause as well.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] For example, high vibration at the frequency corresponding to the speed of rotation is most often due to residual imbalance and is corrected by balancing the machine.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] A degrading rolling-element bearing, on the other hand, will usually exhibit vibration signals at specific frequencies increasing in intensity as it wears.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Special analysis instruments can detect this wear weeks or even months before failure, giving ample warning to schedule replacement before a failure which could cause a much longer down-time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Beside all sensors and data analysis it is important to keep in mind that more than 80% of all complex mechanical equipment fail accidentally and without any relation to their life-cycle period.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Most vibration analysis instruments today utilize a fast Fourier transform (FFT) which is a special case of the generalized discrete Fourier transform and converts the vibration signal from its time domain representation to its equivalent frequency domain representation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] However, frequency analysis (sometimes called Spectral Analysis or Vibration Signature Analysis) is only one aspect of interpreting the information contained in a vibration signal.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Frequency analysis tends to be most useful on machines that employ rolling element bearings and whose main failure modes tend to be the degradation of those bearings, which typically exhibit an increase in characteristic frequencies associated with the bearing geometries and constructions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] This is particularly true of machines that use fluid bearings rather than rolling-element bearings.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Handheld data collectors and analyzers are now commonplace on non-critical or balance of plant machines on which permanent on-line vibration instrumentation cannot be economically justified.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] The technician can collect data samples from a number of machines, then download the data into a computer where the analyst (and sometimes artificial intelligence) can examine the data for changes indicative of malfunctions and impending failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] However, the diagnostic methods and tools available from either approach are generally the same.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Recently also on-line condition monitoring systems have been applied to heavy process industries such as water, steel, oil & gas, pulp & paper, mining, petrochemical and wind power generation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Performance monitoring is a less well-known condition monitoring technique.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] It can be applied to rotating machinery such as pumps and turbines, as well as stationary items such as boilers and heat exchangers.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Measurements are required of physical quantities: temperature, pressure, flow, speed, displacement, according to the plant item.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Absolute accuracy is rarely necessary, but repeatable data is needed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Calibrated test instruments are usually needed, but some success has been achieved in plant with DCS (Distributed Control Systems).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Performance analysis is often closely related to energy efficiency, and therefore has long been applied in steam power generation plants.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] In some cases, it is possible to calculate the optimum time for overhaul to restore degraded performance.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Model-based voltage and current systems (MBVI systems): This is a technique that makes use of the information available from the current and voltage signals across all three phases simultaneously.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Model-based systems are able to identify many of the same phenomena also seen by more conventional techniques, covering electrical, mechanical, and operational areas.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Model-based systems work on the lines shown in Figure 6 below and measure both current and voltage while the motor is in operation and then automatically creates a mathematical model of the relationship between current and voltage.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] By applying this model to the measured voltage, a modelled current is calculated and this is compared with the actual measured current.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] These systems are designed for permanent installation as a condition monitoring solution rather than as a short-term diagnostic measurement device, and their outputs can be integrated into normal plant systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Being permanently connected, historic trends are automatically captured.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] The sort of output that these types of device can create include single screen, traffic light displays of the overall equipment operation, together with diagnosis of a range of mechanical, electrical, and operational problems, and trend plots showing how these parameters are changing through time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] The concept of this type of device is that it can be used by normal plant operators and maintainers without the need for specialist interpretation of spectra, although the underlying spectral plots are available if required.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Because these systems measure both current and voltage, they also monitor power and are able to identify problems caused by unusual operating conditions and identify causes of lost efficiency.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Because model-based systems only examine the difference between actual and predicted currents, they effectively filter out all the normal electrical signals that are so apparent in conventional Motor Current Spectral Analysis (MCSA), leaving a much simpler set of signals to be analysed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Because these systems are based on the relationship between voltage and current, they deal well with inverter driven systems where the input voltage may be of a variable frequency and there may be a noisy waveform high in harmonic components.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Model-based systems effectively filter out all this noise in the voltage signal from the resulting current signal, leaving just the underlying imperfections.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] This ease of use and low cost of this type of equipment makes it appropriate for lower cost, lower criticality equipment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Headphones allow humans to listen to ultrasound as well.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] A high pitched 'buzzing sound' in bearings indicates flaws in the contact surfaces, and when partial blockages occur in high pressure fluids the orifice will cause a large amount of ultrasonic noise.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Essential machinery – Units that are a key part of the process, but if there is a failure, the process still continues.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Redundant units (if available) fall into this realm.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] Testing and control of these units is also essential to maintain alternative plans should critical machinery fail.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/condition-monitoring] General purpose or balance of plant machines – These are the machines that make up the remainder of the plant and normally monitored using a handheld data collector as mentioned previously to periodically create a picture of the health of the machine.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The **industrial Internet of things** (**IIoT**) refers to interconnected sensors, instruments, and other devices networked together with computers' industrial applications, including manufacturing and energy management.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] This connectivity allows for data collection, exchange, and analysis, potentially facilitating improvements in productivity and efficiency as well as other economic benefits.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is an evolution of a distributed control system (DCS) that allows for a higher degree of automation by using cloud computing to refine and optimize the process controls.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is enabled by technologies such as cybersecurity, cloud computing, edge computing, mobile technologies, machine-to-machine, 3D printing, advanced robotics, big data, Internet of things, RFID technology, and cognitive computing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT systems are usually conceived as a layered modular architecture of digital technology.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The device layer refers to the physical components: CPS, sensors or machines.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The network layer consists of physical network buses, cloud computing and communication protocols that aggregate and transport the data to the service layer, which consists of applications that manipulate and combine data into information that can be displayed on the driver dashboard.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The top-most stratum of the stack is the content layer or the user interface.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The history of the IIoT begins with the invention of the programmable logic controller (PLC) by Richard E.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Morley in 1968, which was used by General Motors in their automatic transmission manufacturing division.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] These PLCs allowed for fine control of individual elements in the manufacturing chain.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] In 1975, Honeywell and Yokogawa introduced the world's first DCSs, the TDC 2000 and the CENTUM system, respectively.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] These DCSs were the next step in allowing flexible process control throughout a plant, with the added benefit of backup redundancies by distributing control across the entire system, eliminating a singular point of failure in a central control room.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] As early as in 1994, greater industrial applications were envisioned, as Reza Raji described the concept in IEEE Spectrum as "[moving] small packets of data to a large set of nodes, so as to integrate and automate everything from home appliances to entire factories".
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The concept of the Internet of things first became popular in 1999, through the Auto-ID Center at MIT and related market-analysis publications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Radio-frequency identification (RFID) was seen by Kevin Ashton (one of the founders of the original Auto-ID Center) as a prerequisite for the Internet of things at that point.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] If all objects and people in daily life were equipped with identifiers, computers could manage and inventory them.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Besides using RFID, the tagging of things may be achieved through such technologies as near field communication, barcodes, QR codes and digital watermarking.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the first consequences of implementing the industrial internet of things (by equipping objects with minuscule identifying devices or machine-readable identifiers) would be to create instant and ceaseless inventory control.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Another benefit of implementing an IIoT system is the ability to create a digital twin of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Using this digital twin allows for further optimization of the system by allowing for experimentation with new data from the cloud without having to halt production or sacrifice safety, as the new processes can be refined virtually until they are ready to be implemented.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] A digital twin can also serve as a training ground for new employees who won't have to worry about real impacts on the live system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] IoT frameworks help support the interaction between "things" and allow for more complex structures like distributed computing and the development of distributed applications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The term industrial internet of things is often encountered in the manufacturing industries, referring to the industrial subset of the IoT.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Potential benefits of the industrial internet of things include improved productivity, improved reliability, analytics and the transformation of the workplace.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The potential of growth by implementing IIoT is predicted to generate $15 trillion of global GDP by 2030.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] While connectivity and data acquisition are imperative for IIoT, they are not the end goals, but rather the foundation and path to something bigger.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Of all the technologies, predictive maintenance is an "easier” application, as it is applicable to existing assets and management systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Intelligent maintenance systems can reduce unexpected downtime and increase productivity, which is projected to save up to 12% over scheduled repairs, reduce overall maintenance costs up to 30%, and eliminate breakdowns up to 70%, according to some studies.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Cyber-physical systems (CPS) are the core technology of industrial big data and they will be an interface between human and the cyber world.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Integration of sensing and actuation systems connected to the Internet can optimize energy consumption as a whole.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] It is expected that IoT devices will be integrated into all forms of energy consuming devices (switches, power outlets, bulbs, televisions, etc.) and be able to communicate with the utility supply company in order to effectively balance power generation and energy usage.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) devices connected to the Internet backbone, electric utilities can not only collect data from end-user connections, but also manage other distribution automation devices like transformers and reclosers.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Using IIoT in car manufacturing implies the digitalization of all elements of production.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Software, machines, and humans are interconnected, enabling suppliers and manufacturers to rapidly respond to changing standards.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT enables efficient and cost-effective production by moving data from the customers to the company's systems, and then to individual sections of the production process.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIoT, new tools and functionalities can be included in the manufacturing process.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] For example, 3D printers simplify the way of shaping pressing tools by printing the shape directly from steel granulate.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] These tools enable new possibilities for designing (with high precision).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Customization of vehicles is also enabled by IIoT due to the modularity and connectivity of this technology.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] While in the past they worked separately, IIoT now enables humans and robots to cooperate.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Robots take on heavy and repetitive activities, so the manufacturing cycles are quicker and the vehicle comes to the market more rapidly.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Factories can quickly identify potential maintenance issues before they lead to downtime and many of them are moving to a 24-hour production plant, due to higher security and efficiency.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The majority of automotive manufacturers companies have production plants in different countries, where different components of the same vehicle are built.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT makes it possible to connect these production plants to each other, creating the possibility to move within facilities.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Big data can be visually monitored which enables companies to respond faster to fluctuations in production and demand.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT support, large amounts of raw data can be stored and sent by the drilling gear and research stations for cloud storage and analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT technologies, the oil and gas industry has the capability to connect machines, devices, sensors, and people through interconnectivity, which can help companies better address fluctuations in demand and pricing, address cybersecurity, and minimize environmental impact.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Across the supply chain, IIOT can improve the maintenance process, the overall safety, and connectivity.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Drones can be used to detect possible oil and gas leaks at an early stage and at locations that are difficult to reach (e.g. offshore).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] They can also be used to identify weak spots in complex networks of pipelines with built-in thermal imaging systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Increased connectivity (data integration and communication) can help companies with adjusting the production levels based on real-time data of inventory, storage, distribution pace, and forecasted demand.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows monitoring of pipeline threats, improving risk management, and providing situational awareness.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Benefits also apply to specific processes of the oil and gas industry.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The exploration process of oil and gas can be done more precisely with 4D models built by seismic imaging.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] These models map fluctuations in oil reserves and gas levels, they strive to point out the exact quantity of resources needed, and they forecast the lifespan of wells.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The application of smart sensors and automated drillers gives companies the opportunity to monitor and produce more efficiently.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Further, the storing process can also be improved with the implementation of IIOT by collecting and analyzing real-time data to monitor inventory levels and temperature control.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIOT can enhance the transportation process of oil and gas by implementing smart sensors and thermal detectors to give real-time geolocation data and monitor the products for safety reasons.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] These smart sensors can monitor the refinery processes, and enhance safety.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The demand for products can be forecasted more precisely and automatically be communicated to the refineries and production plants to adjust production levels.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] In the agriculture industry, IIoT helps farmers to make decisions about when to harvest.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Sensors collect data about soil and weather conditions and propose schedules for fertilizing and irrigating.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Some livestock farms implant microchips into animals.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows the farmers not only to trace their animals, but also pull up information about the lineage, weight, or health.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The integration of IIoT data in the photovoltaic (PV) industry can significantly enhance the efficiency, reliability, and performance of solar power systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT with AI data can be utilized for real-time monitoring, performance optimization, fault detection, diagnostics.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] As the IIoT expands, new security concerns arise with it.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Every new device or component that connects to the IIoT can become a potential liability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Gartner estimates that by 2020, more than 25% of recognized attacks on enterprises will involve IoT-connected systems, despite accounting for less than 10% of IT security budgets.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Existing cybersecurity measures are vastly inferior for Internet-connected devices compared to their traditional computer counterparts, which can allow for them to be hijacked for DDoS-based attacks by botnets like Mirai.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Another possibility is the infection of Internet-connected industrial controllers, like in the case of Stuxnet, without the need for physical access to the system to spread the worm.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Additionally, IIoT-enabled devices can allow for more “traditional” forms of cybercrime, as in the case of the 2013 Target data breach, where information was stolen after hackers gained access to Target's networks via credentials stolen from a third party HVAC vendor.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] The pharmaceutical manufacturing industry has been slow to adopt IIoT advances because of security concerns such as these.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the difficulties in providing security solutions in IIoT applications is the fragmented nature of the hardware.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Consequently, security architectures are turning towards designs that are software-based or device-agnostic.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/industrial-internet-of-things] Hardware-based approaches, like the use of data diodes, are often used when connecting critical infrastructure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] The main appeal of predictive maintenance is to allow convenient scheduling of corrective maintenance, and to prevent unexpected equipment failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] By taking into account measurements of the state of the equipment, maintenance work can be better planned (spare parts, people, etc.) and what would have been "unplanned stops" are transformed to shorter and fewer "planned stops", thus increasing plant availability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Other potential advantages include increased equipment lifetime, increased plant safety, fewer accidents with negative impact on environment, and optimized spare parts handling.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Predictive maintenance differs from preventive maintenance because it does take into account the current condition of equipment (with measurements), instead of average or expected life statistics, to predict when maintenance will be required.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Machine Learning approaches are adopted for the forecasting of its future states.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Some of the main components that are necessary for implementing predictive maintenance are data collection and preprocessing, early fault detection, fault detection, time to failure prediction, and maintenance scheduling and resource optimization.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Predictive maintenance has been considered one of the driving forces for improving productivity and a way to achieve just-in-time manufacturing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Predictive maintenance evaluates the condition of equipment by performing periodic (offline) or continuous (online) equipment condition monitoring.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] The ultimate goal of the approach is to perform maintenance at a scheduled point in time when the maintenance activity is most cost-effective and before the equipment loses performance within a threshold.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This results in a reduction in unplanned downtime costs because of failure, where costs can be in the hundreds of thousands per day depending on industry.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] In energy production, in addition to loss of revenue and component costs, fines can be levied for non-delivery, increasing costs even further.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This is in contrast to time- and/or operation count-based maintenance, where a piece of equipment gets maintained whether it needs it or not.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Time-based maintenance is labor intensive, ineffective in identifying problems that develop between scheduled inspections, and therefore is not cost-effective.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] The "predictive" component of predictive maintenance stems from the goal of predicting the future trend of the equipment's condition.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This approach uses principles of statistical process control to determine at what point in the future maintenance activities will be appropriate.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Most predictive inspections are performed while equipment is in service, thereby minimizing disruption of normal system operations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Adoption of predictive maintenance can result in substantial cost savings and higher system reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] In today's dynamic landscape of service maintenance, prolonged repair processes present a significant challenge for organizations striving to maintain operational excellence.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Extended downtime, increased Mean Time to Repair (MTTR), and production losses not only affect profitability but also disrupt service continuity and diminish customer satisfaction.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] As equipment ages and maintenance requirements intensify, the quest for innovative solutions becomes increasingly urgent.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] One goal is to transfer the predictive maintenance data to a computerized maintenance management system so that the equipment condition data is sent to the right equipment object to trigger maintenance planning, work order execution, and reporting.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Unless this is achieved, the predictive maintenance solution is of limited value, at least if the solution is implemented on a medium to large size plant with tens of thousands pieces of equipment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] To evaluate equipment condition, predictive maintenance utilizes nondestructive testing technologies such as infrared, acoustic (partial discharge and airborne ultrasonic), corona detection, vibration analysis, sound level measurements, oil analysis, and other specific online tests.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] A new approach in this area is to utilize measurements on the actual equipment in combination with measurement of process performance, measured by other devices, to trigger equipment maintenance.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This is primarily available in collaborative process automation systems (CPAS).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Site measurements are often supported by wireless sensor networks to reduce the wiring cost.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Vibration analysis is most productive on high-speed rotating equipment and can be the most expensive component of a PdM program to get up and running.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Vibration analysis, when properly done, allows the user to evaluate the condition of equipment and avoid failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] The latest generation of vibration analyzers comprises more capabilities and automated functions than its predecessors.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Many units display the full vibration spectrum of three axes simultaneously, providing a snapshot of what is going on with a particular machine.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] But despite such capabilities, not even the most sophisticated equipment successfully predicts developing problems unless the operator understands and applies the basics of vibration analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] In certain situations, strong background noise interferences from several competing sources may mask the signal of interest and hinder the industrial applicability of vibration sensors.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Consequently, motor current signature analysis (MCSA) is a non-intrusive alternative to vibration measurement which has the potential to monitor faults from both electrical and mechanical systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Remote visual inspection is the first non-destructive testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] It provides a cost-efficient primary assessment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Essential information and defaults can be deduced from the external appearance of the piece, such as folds, breaks, cracks, and corrosion.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] The remote visual inspection has to be carried out in good conditions with a sufficient lighting (350 LUX at least).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] When the part of the piece to be controlled is not directly accessible, an instrument made of mirrors and lenses called endoscope is used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Hidden defects with external irregularities may indicate a more serious defect inside.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Acoustical analysis can be done on a sonic or ultrasonic level.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] New ultrasonic techniques for condition monitoring make it possible to "hear" friction and stress in rotating machinery, which can predict deterioration earlier than conventional techniques.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Ultrasonic technology is sensitive to high-frequency sounds that are inaudible to the human ear and distinguishes them from lower-frequency sounds and mechanical vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Machine friction and stress waves produce distinctive sounds in the upper ultrasonic range.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Changes in these friction and stress waves can suggest deteriorating conditions much earlier than technologies such as vibration or oil analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] With proper ultrasonic measurement and analysis, it's possible to differentiate normal wear from abnormal wear, physical damage, imbalance conditions, and lubrication problems based on a direct relationship between asset and operating conditions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Sonic monitoring equipment is less expensive, but it also has fewer uses than ultrasonic technologies.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Sonic technology is useful only on mechanical equipment, while ultrasonic equipment can detect electrical problems and is more flexible and reliable in detecting mechanical problems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Infrared monitoring and analysis has the widest range of application (from high- to low-speed equipment), and it can be effective for spotting both mechanical and electrical failures; some consider it to currently be the most cost-effective technology.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Oil analysis is a long-term program that, where relevant, can eventually be more predictive than any of the other technologies.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] It can take years for a plant's oil program to reach this level of sophistication and effectiveness.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Analytical techniques performed on oil samples can be classified in two categories: used oil analysis and wear particle analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Used oil analysis determines the condition of the lubricant itself, determines the quality of the lubricant, and checks its suitability for continued use.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Wear particle analysis determines the mechanical condition of machine components that are lubricated.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Through wear particle analysis, you can identify the composition of the solid material present and evaluate particle type, size, concentration, distribution, and morphology.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Model-based condition monitoring is another approach used in predictive maintenance programs.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] It involves analyzing electrical signals, such as motor current and voltage, and comparing measured parameters to a reference model in order to identify deviations associated with faults.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This method has been applied in aerospace and industrial systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Model-based systems can support automated data analysis and continuous monitoring.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] Additional predictive maintenance methods include various data-driven and smart testing strategies.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] An application of predictive maintenance is in the automotive and transportation sectors, particularly in fleet management.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] The process relies on telematics to collect real-time data from vehicles.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] A telematic control unit installed in a vehicle continuously gathers telemetry from the engine's CAN bus, including diagnostic trouble codes (DTCs), fuel consumption, and component status.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This data is then transmitted to a fleet telematics system, where machine learning algorithms analyze it to detect patterns that precede failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This allows the system to predict potential issues with critical components, such as the battery, starter motor, or brakes, before they result in a breakdown.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/predictive-maintenance] This approach is a component of modern fleet digitalization, enabling businesses to schedule maintenance at a cost-effective time, reduce unplanned downtime, and improve vehicle reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Data-driven prognostics usually use pattern recognition and machine learning techniques to detect changes in system states.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The classical data-driven methods for nonlinear system prediction include the use of stochastic models such as the autoregressive (AR) model, the threshold AR model, the bilinear model, the projection pursuit, the multivariate adaptive regression splines, and the Volterra series expansion.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Since the last decade, more interests in data-driven system state forecasting have been focused on the use of flexible models such as various types of neural networks (NNs) and neural fuzzy (NF) systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Data-driven approaches are appropriate when the understanding of first principles of system operation is not comprehensive or when the system is sufficiently complex such that developing an accurate model is prohibitively expensive.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Therefore, the principal advantages to data driven approaches is that they can often be deployed quicker and cheaper compared to other approaches, and that they can provide system-wide coverage (cf. physics-based models, which can be quite narrow in scope).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The main disadvantage is that data driven approaches may have wider confidence intervals than other approaches and that they require a substantial amount of data for training.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Data-driven approaches can be further subcategorized into fleet-based statistics and sensor-based conditioning.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] In addition, data-driven techniques also subsume cycle-counting techniques that may include domain knowledge.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The two basic data-driven strategies involve (1) modeling cumulative damage (or, equivalently, health) and then extrapolating out to a damage (or health) threshold, or (2) learning directly from data the remaining useful life.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] As mentioned, a principal bottleneck is the difficulty in obtaining run-to-failure data, in particular for new systems, since running systems to failure can be a lengthy and rather costly process.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] When future usage is not the same as in the past (as with most non-stationary systems), collecting data that includes all possible future usages (both load and environmental conditions) becomes often nearly impossible.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Even where data exist, the efficacy of data-driven approaches is not only dependent on the quantity but also on the quality of system operational data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] These data sources may include temperature, pressure, oil debris, currents, voltages, power, vibration and acoustic signal, spectrometric data as well as calibration and calorimetric data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The data often needs to be pre-processed before it can be used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Typically two procedures are performed i) Denoising and ii) Feature extraction.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Denoising refers to reducing or eliminating the influence of noise on data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Features extraction is important because in today's data hungry world, a huge amount of data is collected using sensor measurement that may not be used readily.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Therefore, domain knowledge and statistical signal processing is applied to extract important features from (more often than not) noisy, high-dimensional data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Physics-based prognostics (sometimes called model-based prognostics) attempts to incorporate physical understanding (physical models) of the system into the estimation of remaining useful life (RUL).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Modeling physics can be accomplished at different levels, for example, micro and macro levels.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The micro-level models are often referred as damage propagation models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] For example, Yu and Harris's fatigue life model for ball bearings, which relates the fatigue life of a bearing to the induced stress, Paris and Erdogan's crack growth model, and stochastic defect-propagation model are other examples of micro-level models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Since measurements of critical damage properties (such as stress or strain of a mechanical component) are rarely available, sensed system parameters have to be used to infer the stress/strain values.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Micro-level models need to account in the uncertainty management for the assumptions and simplifications, which may pose significant limitations of that approach.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Macro-level models are the mathematical model at system level, which defines the relationship among system input variables, system state variables, and system measures variables/outputs where the model is often a somewhat simplified representation of the system, for example a lumped parameter model.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The trade-off is increased coverage with possibly reducing accuracy of a particular degradation mode.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Where this trade-off is permissible, faster prototyping may be the result.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] However, where systems are complex (e.g., a gas turbine engine), even a macro-level model may be a rather time-consuming and labor-intensive process.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] As a result, macro-level models may not be available in detail for all subsystems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The resulting simplifications need to be accounted for by the uncertainty management.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Hybrid approaches attempt to leverage the strength from both data-driven approaches as well as model-based approaches.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] In reality, it is rare that the fielded approaches are completely either purely data-driven or purely model-based.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] More often than not, model-based approaches include some aspects of data-driven approaches and data-driven approaches glean available information from models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] An example for the former would be where model parameters are tuned using field data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] An example for the latter is when the set-point, bias, or normalization factor for a data-driven approach is given by models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Hybrid approaches can be categorized broadly into two categories, 1) Pre-estimate fusion and 2) Post-estimate fusion.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Physics-based and empirical models may be combined in a simple additive fashion as well, such as an additive combination of a basic physics-based model with an artificial neural network.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] This could deliver superior diagnostic or prognostic performance compared to just one or the other.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] See, for example, such an additive hybrid model employed in jet engine performance analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The motivation for pre-estimate aggregation may be that no ground truth data are available.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] This may occur in situations where diagnostics does a good job in detecting faults that are resolved (through maintenance) before system failure occurs.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Therefore, there are hardly any run-to-failure data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] However, there is incentive to know better when a system would fail to better leverage the remaining useful life while at the same time avoiding unscheduled maintenance (unscheduled maintenance is typically more costly than scheduled maintenance and results in system downtime).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Garga et al. describe conceptually a pre-estimate aggregation hybrid approach where domain knowledge is used to change the structure of a neural network, thus resulting in a more parsimonious representation of the network.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] For example, Khorasgani et al. modeled the physics of failure in electrolytic capacitors.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Then, they used a particle filter approach to derive the dynamic form of the degradation model and estimate the current state of capacitor health.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] This model is then used to get more accurate estimation of the Remaining Useful Life (RUL) of the capacitors as they are subjected to thermal stress conditions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Motivation for post-estimate fusion is often a consideration of uncertainty management.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] That is, the post-estimate fusion helps to narrow the uncertainty intervals of data-driven or model-based approaches.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] At the same time, the accuracy improves.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The underlying notion is that multiple information sources can help to improve performance of an estimator.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] This principle has been successfully applied within the context of classifier fusion, where the output of multiple classifiers is used to arrive at a better result than any classifier alone.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Within the context of prognostics, fusion can be accomplished by employing quality assessments that are assigned to the individual estimators based on a variety of inputs, for example heuristics, a priori known performance, prediction horizon, or robustness of the prediction.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Prognostic performance evaluation is of key importance for a successful PHM system deployment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The early lack of standardized methods for performance evaluation and benchmark data-sets resulted in reliance on conventional performance metrics borrowed from statistics.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Those metrics were primarily accuracy and precision based, where performance is evaluated against end of life, typically known a priori in an offline setting.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] More recently, efforts towards maturing prognostics technology have put a significant focus on standardizing prognostic methods, including those of performance assessment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] A key aspect, missing from the conventional metrics, is the capability to track performance with time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] This is important because prognostics is a dynamic process where predictions get updated with an appropriate frequency as more observation data become available from an operational system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Similarly, the performance of prediction changes with time that must be tracked and quantified.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Another aspect that makes this process different in a PHM context is the time value of a RUL prediction.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] As a system approaches failure, the time window to take a corrective action gets shorter and consequently the accuracy of predictions becomes more critical for decision making.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Finally, randomness and noise in the process, measurements, and prediction models are unavoidable and hence prognostics inevitably involves uncertainty in its estimates.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] A robust prognostics performance evaluation must incorporate the effects of this uncertainty.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] A visual representation of these metrics can be used to depict prognostic performance over a long time horizon.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] There are many uncertainty parameters that can influence the prediction accuracy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] For most PHM industrial applications, commercial off the shelf data acquisition hardware and sensors are normally the most practical and common.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Example commercial vendors for data acquisition hardware include National Instruments and Advantech Webaccess; however, for certain applications, the hardware can be customized or ruggedized as needed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Common sensor types for PHM applications include accelerometers, temperature, pressure, measurements of rotational speed using encoders or tachometers, electrical measurements of voltage and current, acoustic emission, load cells for force measurements, and displacement or position measurements.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] There are numerous sensor vendors for those measurement types, with some having a specific product line that is more suited for condition monitoring and PHM applications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] The data analysis algorithms and pattern recognition technology are now being offered in some commercial software platforms or as part of a packaged software solution.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] National Instruments currently has a trial version (with a commercial release in the upcoming year) of the Watchdog Agent prognostic toolkit, which is a collection of data-driven PHM algorithms that were developed by the Center for Intelligent Maintenance Systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] This collection of over 20 tools allows one to configure and customize the algorithms for signature extraction, anomaly detection, health assessment, failure diagnosis, and failure prediction for a given application as needed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Another example is MATLAB and its Predictive Maintenance Toolbox which provides functions and an interactive app for exploring, extracting, and ranking features using data-based and model-based techniques, including statistical, spectral, and time-series analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] This toolbox also includes reference examples for motors, gearboxes, batteries, and other machines that can be reused for developing custom predictive maintenance and condition monitoring algorithms.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Other commercial software offerings focus on a few tools for anomaly detection and fault diagnosis, and are typically offered as a package solution instead of a toolkit offering.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/prognostics] Similar types of analysis methods are also offered by Expert Microsystems, which uses a similar auto-associative kernel method for calculating residuals, and has other modules for diagnosis and prediction.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In mechanics, **vibration** (from Latin *vibrāre* 'to shake') is an oscillation of matter about an equilibrium point.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibration may be deterministic if the oscillations can be characterised precisely (e.g. the periodic motion of a pendulum), or random if the oscillations can only be analysed statistically (e.g. the movement of a tire on a gravel road).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibration can be desirable: for example, the motion of a tuning fork, the reed in a woodwind instrument or harmonica, a mobile phone, or the cone of a loudspeaker.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In many cases, however, vibration is undesirable, wasting energy and creating unwanted sound.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For example, the vibrational motions of engines, electric motors, or any mechanical device in operation are typically unwanted.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Such vibrations could be caused by imbalances in the rotating parts, uneven friction, or the meshing of gear teeth.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Careful designs usually minimize unwanted vibrations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The studies of sound and vibration are closely related (both fall under acoustics).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Sound, or pressure waves, are generated by vibrating structures (e.g. vocal cords); these pressure waves can also induce the vibration of structures (e.g. ear drum).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Hence, attempts to reduce noise are often related to issues of vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Machining vibrations are common in the process of subtractive manufacturing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibration isolation is the prevention of transmission of vibration from one component of a system to other parts of the same system, as in buildings or mechanical systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibration is undesirable in many domains, primarily engineered systems and habitable spaces, and methods have been developed to prevent the transfer of vibration to such systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibrations propagate via mechanical waves and certain mechanical linkages conduct vibrations more efficiently than others.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Passive vibration isolation makes use of materials and mechanical linkages that absorb and damp these mechanical waves.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Active vibration isolation involves sensors and actuators that produce disruptive interference that cancels-out incoming vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibration testing is accomplished by introducing a forcing function into a structure, usually with some type of shaker.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Alternately, a DUT (device under test) is attached to the "table" of a shaker.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibration testing is performed to examine the response of a device under test (DUT) to a defined vibration environment.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The measured response may be ability to function in the vibration environment, fatigue life, resonant frequencies or squeak and rattle sound output (NVH).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Squeak and rattle testing is performed with a special type of *quiet shaker* that produces very low sound levels while under operation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For relatively low frequency forcing (typically less than 100 Hz), servohydraulic (electrohydraulic) shakers are used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For higher frequencies (typically 5 Hz to 2000 Hz), electrodynamic shakers are used.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Generally, one or more "input" or "control" points located on the DUT-side of a vibration fixture is kept at a specified acceleration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Other "response" points may experience higher vibration levels (resonance) or lower vibration level (anti-resonance or damping) than the control point(s).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] It is often desirable to achieve anti-resonance to keep a system from becoming too noisy, or to reduce strain on certain parts due to vibration modes caused by specific vibration frequencies.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The most common types of vibration testing services conducted by vibration test labs are sinusoidal and random.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Sine (one-frequency-at-a-time) tests are performed to survey the structural response of the device under test (DUT).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] During the early history of vibration testing, vibration machine controllers were limited only to controlling sine motion so only sine testing was performed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Later, more sophisticated analog and then digital controllers were able to provide random control (all frequencies at once).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] A random (all frequencies at once) test is generally considered to more closely replicate a real world environment, such as road inputs to a moving automobile.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Most vibration testing is conducted in a 'single DUT axis' at a time, even though most real-world vibration occurs in various axes simultaneously.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] MIL-STD-810G, released in late 2008, Test Method 527, calls for multiple exciter testing.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The *vibration test fixture* used to attach the DUT to the shaker table must be designed for the frequency range of the vibration test spectrum.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] It is difficult to design a vibration test fixture which duplicates the dynamic response (mechanical impedance) of the actual in-use mounting.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For this reason, to ensure repeatability between vibration tests, vibration fixtures are designed to be resonance free within the test frequency range.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Generally for smaller fixtures and lower frequency ranges, the designer can target a fixture design that is free of resonances in the test frequency range.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This becomes more difficult as the DUT gets larger and as the test frequency increases.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In these cases multi-point control strategies can mitigate some of the resonances that may be present in the future.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Some vibration test methods limit the amount of crosstalk (movement of a response point in a mutually perpendicular direction to the axis under test) permitted to be exhibited by the vibration test fixture.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Devices specifically designed to trace or record vibrations are called vibroscopes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibration analysis (VA), applied in an industrial or maintenance environment aims to reduce maintenance costs and equipment downtime by detecting equipment faults.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] VA is a key component of a condition monitoring (CM) program, and is often referred to as predictive maintenance (PdM).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Most commonly VA is used to detect faults in rotating equipment (Fans, Motors, Pumps, and Gearboxes etc.) such as imbalance, misalignment, rolling element bearing faults and resonance conditions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] VA can use the units of Displacement, Velocity and Acceleration displayed as a time waveform (TWF), but most commonly the spectrum is used, derived from a fast Fourier transform of the TWF.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The vibration spectrum provides important frequency information that can pinpoint the faulty component.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The fundamentals of vibration analysis can be understood by studying the simple Mass-spring-damper model.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Indeed, even a complex structure such as an automobile body can be modeled as a "summation" of simple mass–spring–damper models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The mass–spring–damper model is an example of a simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The mathematics used to describe its behavior is identical to other simple harmonic oscillators such as the RLC circuit.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Note: This article does not include the step-by-step mathematical derivations, but focuses on major vibration analysis equations and concepts.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Please refer to the references at the end of the article for detailed derivations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] To start the investigation of the mass–spring–damper assume the damping is negligible and that there is no external force applied to the mass (i.e. free vibration).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The force applied to the mass by the spring is proportional to the amount the spring is stretched "x" (assuming the spring is already compressed due to the weight of the mass).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The proportionality constant, k, is the stiffness of the spring and has units of force/distance (e.g. lbf/in or N/m).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This solution says that it will oscillate with simple harmonic motion that has an amplitude of *A* and a frequency of *fn*.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The number *fn* is called the **undamped natural frequency**.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Note: angular frequency ω (ω=2 π *f*) with the units of radians per second is often used in equations because it simplifies the equations, but is normally converted to ordinary frequency (units of Hz or equivalently cycles per second) when stating the frequency of a system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] If the mass and stiffness of the system is known, the formula above can determine the frequency at which the system vibrates once set in motion by an initial disturbance.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Every vibrating system has one or more natural frequencies that it vibrates at once disturbed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This simple relation can be used to understand in general what happens to a more complex system once we add mass or stiffness.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For example, the above formula explains why, when a car or truck is fully loaded, the suspension feels "softer" than unloaded—the mass has increased, reducing the natural frequency of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Vibrational motion could be understood in terms of conservation of energy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In the above example the spring has been extended by a value of x and therefore some potential energy ( ${\tfrac {1}{2}}kx^{2}$ ) is stored in the spring.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Once released, the spring tends to return to its un-stretched state (which is the minimum potential energy state) and in the process accelerates the mass.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] At the point where the spring has reached its un-stretched state all the potential energy that we supplied by stretching it has been transformed into kinetic energy ( ${\tfrac {1}{2}}mv^{2}$ ).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The mass then begins to decelerate because it is now compressing the spring and in the process transferring the kinetic energy back to its potential.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Thus oscillation of the spring amounts to the transferring back and forth of the kinetic energy into potential energy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In this simple model the mass continues to oscillate forever at the same magnitude—but in a real system, *damping* always dissipates the energy, eventually bringing the spring to rest.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] When a dashpot is added, this models sources of damping by generating a force that is proportional to the velocity of the mass.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The proportionality constant *c* is called the damping coefficient and has units of Force over velocity (lbf⋅s/in or N⋅s/m).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The solution to this equation depends on the amount of damping.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] If the damping is small enough, the system still vibrates—but eventually, over time, stops vibrating.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This case is called underdamping, which is important in vibration analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] If damping is increased just to the point where the system no longer oscillates, the system has reached the point of critical damping.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] If the damping is increased past critical damping, the system is overdamped.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The damping ratio is used to characterize the amount of damping in a system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This is a ratio of the actual damping over the amount of damping required to reach critical damping.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For example, metal structures (e.g., airplane fuselages, engine crankshafts) have damping factors less than 0.05, while automotive suspensions are in the range of 0.2–0.3.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The value of *X*, the initial magnitude, and $\phi ,$ the phase shift, are determined by the amount the spring is stretched.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The formulas for these values can be found in the references.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The major points to note from the solution are the exponential term and the cosine function.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The exponential term defines how quickly the system “damps” down – the larger the damping ratio, the quicker it damps to zero.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The cosine function is the oscillating portion of the solution, but the frequency of the oscillations is different from the undamped case.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The damped natural frequency is less than the undamped natural frequency, but for many practical cases the damping ratio is relatively small and hence the difference is negligible.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Therefore, the damped and undamped description are often dropped when stating the natural frequency (e.g. with 0.1 damping ratio, the damped natural frequency is only 1% less than the undamped).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The plots to the side present how 0.1 and 0.3 damping ratios affect how the system "rings" down over time.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] What is often done in practice is to experimentally measure the free vibration after an impact (for example by a hammer) and then determine the natural frequency of the system by measuring the rate of oscillation, as well as the damping ratio by measuring the rate of decay.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The natural frequency and damping ratio are not only important in free vibration, but also characterize how a system behaves under forced vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Both the damped and undamped natural frequencies can be estimate when the mode shapes are not known using the Rayleigh Quotient.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The behavior of the spring mass damper model varies with the addition of a harmonic force.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] A force of this type could, for example, be generated by a rotating imbalance.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The amplitude of the vibration “X” is defined by the following formula.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Where “r” is defined as the ratio of the harmonic force frequency over the undamped natural frequency of the mass–spring–damper model.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The phase shift, $\phi ,$ is defined by the following formula.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] (Forced Vibration Response) The plot of these functions, called "the frequency response of the system", presents one of the most important features in forced vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In a lightly damped system when the forcing frequency nears the natural frequency ( $r\approx 1$ ) the amplitude of the vibration can get extremely high.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This phenomenon is called **resonance** (subsequently the natural frequency of a system is often referred to as the resonant frequency).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In rotor bearing systems any rotational speed that excites a resonant frequency is referred to as a critical speed.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] If resonance occurs in a mechanical system it can be very harmful – leading to eventual failure of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Consequently, one of the major reasons for vibration analysis is to predict when this type of resonance may occur and then to determine what steps to take to prevent it from occurring.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] As the amplitude plot shows, adding damping can significantly reduce the magnitude of the vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Also, the magnitude can be reduced if the natural frequency can be shifted away from the forcing frequency by changing the stiffness or mass of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] If the system cannot be changed, perhaps the forcing frequency can be shifted (for example, changing the speed of the machine generating the force).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The following are some other points in regards to the forced vibration shown in the frequency response plots.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Resonance is simple to understand if the spring and mass are viewed as energy storage elements – with the mass storing kinetic energy and the spring storing potential energy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] As discussed earlier, when the mass and spring have no external force acting on them they transfer energy back and forth at a rate equal to the natural frequency.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In other words, to efficiently pump energy into both mass and spring requires that the energy source feed the energy in at a rate equal to the natural frequency.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Applying a force to the mass and spring is similar to pushing a child on swing, a push is needed at the correct moment to make the swing get higher and higher.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] As in the case of the swing, the force applied need not be high to get large motions, but must just add energy to the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The damper, instead of storing energy, dissipates energy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Since the damping force is proportional to the velocity, the more the motion, the more the damper dissipates the energy.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Therefore, there is a point when the energy dissipated by the damper equals the energy added by the force.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] At this point, the system has reached its maximum amplitude and will continue to vibrate at this level as long as the force applied stays the same.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] If no damping exists, there is nothing to dissipate the energy and, theoretically, the motion will continue to grow into infinity.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In a previous section only a simple harmonic force was applied to the model, but this can be extended considerably using two powerful mathematical tools.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The first is the Fourier transform that takes a signal as a function of time (time domain) and breaks it down into its harmonic components as a function of frequency (frequency domain).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For example, by applying a force to the mass–spring–damper model that repeats the following cycle – a force equal to 1 newton for 0.5 second and then no force for 0.5 second.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This type of force has the shape of a 1 Hz square wave.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The Fourier transform of the square wave generates a frequency spectrum that presents the magnitude of the harmonics that make up the square wave (the phase is also generated, but is typically of less concern and therefore is often not plotted).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The Fourier transform can also be used to analyze non-periodic functions such as transients (e.g. impulses) and random functions.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The Fourier transform is almost always computed using the fast Fourier transform (FFT) computer algorithm in combination with a window function.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In the case of our square wave force, the first component is actually a constant force of 0.5 newton and is represented by a value at 0 Hz in the frequency spectrum.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The next component is a 1 Hz sine wave with an amplitude of 0.64.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The remaining components are at odd frequencies and it takes an infinite amount of sine waves to generate the perfect square wave.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Hence, the Fourier transform allows you to interpret the force as a sum of sinusoidal forces being applied instead of a more "complex" force (e.g. a square wave).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In the previous section, the vibration solution was given for a single harmonic force, but the Fourier transform in general gives multiple harmonic forces.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The second mathematical tool, the superposition principle, allows the summation of the solutions from multiple forces if the system is linear.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In the case of the spring–mass–damper model, the system is linear if the spring force is proportional to the displacement and the damping is proportional to the velocity over the range of motion of interest.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Hence, the solution to the problem with a square wave is summing the predicted vibration from each one of the harmonic forces found in the frequency spectrum of the square wave.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The solution of a vibration problem can be viewed as an input/output relation – where the force is the input and the output is the vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] $H(i\omega )$ is called the frequency response function (also referred to as the transfer function, but not technically as accurate) and has both a magnitude and phase component (if represented as a complex number, a real and imaginary component).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The magnitude of the frequency response function (FRF) was presented earlier for the mass–spring–damper system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For example, calculating the FRF for a mass–spring–damper system with a mass of 1 kg, spring stiffness of 1.93 N/mm and a damping ratio of 0.1.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The values of the spring and mass give a natural frequency of 7 Hz for this specific system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Applying the 1 Hz square wave from earlier allows the calculation of the predicted vibration of the mass.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The figure illustrates the resulting vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] It happens in this example that the fourth harmonic of the square wave falls at 7 Hz.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The frequency response of the mass–spring–damper therefore outputs a high 7 Hz vibration even though the input force had a relatively low 7 Hz harmonic.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This example highlights that the resulting vibration is dependent on both the forcing function and the system that the force is applied to.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The figure also shows the time domain representation of the resulting vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This is done by performing an inverse Fourier Transform that converts frequency domain data to time domain.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In practice, this is rarely done because the frequency spectrum provides all the necessary information.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The frequency response function (FRF) does not necessarily have to be calculated from the knowledge of the mass, damping, and stiffness of the system—but can be measured experimentally.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] For example, if a known force over a range of frequencies is applied, and if the associated vibrations are measured, the frequency response function can be calculated, thereby characterizing the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This technique is used in the field of experimental modal analysis to determine the vibration characteristics of a structure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The simple mass–spring–damper model is the foundation of vibration analysis.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The model described above is called a single degree of freedom (SDOF) model since the mass is assumed to only move up and down.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In more complex systems, the system must be discretized into more masses that move in more than one direction, adding degrees of freedom.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The major concepts of multiple degrees of freedom (MDOF) can be understood by looking at just a two degree of freedom model as shown in the figure.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] where ${\begin{bmatrix}M\end{bmatrix}},$ ${\begin{bmatrix}C\end{bmatrix}},$ and ${\begin{bmatrix}K\end{bmatrix}}$ are symmetric matrices referred respectively as the mass, damping, and stiffness matrices.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The matrices are NxN square matrices where N is the number of degrees of freedom of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The following analysis involves the case where there is no damping and no applied forces (i.e. free vibration).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The solution of a viscously damped system is somewhat more complicated.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Note: Using the exponential solution of ${\begin{Bmatrix}X\end{Bmatrix}}e^{i\omega t}$ is a mathematical trick used to solve linear differential equations.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Using Euler's formula and taking only the real part of the solution it is the same cosine solution for the 1 DOF system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The exponential solution is only used because it is easier to manipulate mathematically.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Since $e^{i\omega t}$ cannot equal zero the equation reduces to the following.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The solution to the problem results in N **eigenvalues** (i.e. $\omega _{1}^{2},\omega _{2}^{2},\cdots \omega _{N}^{2}$ ), where N corresponds to the number of degrees of freedom.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The eigenvalues provide the natural frequencies of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] When these eigenvalues are substituted back into the original set of equations, the values of ${\begin{Bmatrix}X\end{Bmatrix}}$ that correspond to each eigenvalue are called the **eigenvectors**.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] These eigenvectors represent the mode shapes of the system.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The solution of an eigenvalue problem can be quite cumbersome (especially for problems with many degrees of freedom), but fortunately most math analysis programs have eigenvalue routines.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] A simple example using the 2 DOF model can help illustrate the concepts.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Let both masses have a mass of 1 kg and the stiffness of all three springs equal 1000 N/m.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Since the system is a 2 DOF system, there are two modes with their respective natural frequencies and shapes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The mode shape vectors are not the absolute motion, but just describe relative motion of the degrees of freedom.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In our case the first mode shape vector is saying that the masses are moving together in phase since they have the same value and sign.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In the case of the second mode shape vector, each mass is moving in opposite direction at the same rate.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] When there are many degrees of freedom, one method of visualizing the mode shapes is by animating them using structural analysis software such as Femap, ANSYS or VA One by ESI Group.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] An example of animating mode shapes is shown in the figure below for a cantilevered Ɪ-beam as demonstrated using modal analysis on ANSYS.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In this case, the finite element method was used to generate an approximation of the mass and stiffness matrices by meshing the object of interest in order to solve a discrete eigenvalue problem.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Note that, in this case, the finite element method provides an approximation of the meshed surface (for which there exists an infinite number of vibration modes and frequencies).
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Therefore, this relatively simple model that has over 100 degrees of freedom and hence as many natural frequencies and mode shapes, provides a good approximation for the first natural frequencies and modes†.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Generally, only the first few modes are important for practical applications.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The eigenvectors have very important properties called orthogonality properties.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] These properties can be used to greatly simplify the solution of multi-degree of freedom models.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] ${\begin{bmatrix}^{\diagdown }m_{r\diagdown }\end{bmatrix}}$ and ${\begin{bmatrix}^{\diagdown }k_{r\diagdown }\end{bmatrix}}$ are diagonal matrices that contain the modal mass and stiffness values for each one of the modes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] (Note: Since the eigenvectors (mode shapes) can be arbitrarily scaled, the orthogonality properties are often used to scale the eigenvectors so the modal mass value for each mode is equal to 1.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] These properties can be used to greatly simplify the solution of multi-degree of freedom models by making the following coordinate transformation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Using this coordinate transformation in the original free vibration differential equation results in the following equation.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] This equation is the foundation of vibration analysis for multiple degree of freedom systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] A similar type of result can be derived for damped systems.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The key is that the modal mass and stiffness matrices are diagonal matrices and therefore the equations have been "decoupled".
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] In other words, the problem has been transformed from a large unwieldy multiple degree of freedom problem into many single degree of freedom problems that can be solved using the same methods outlined above.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Solving for *x* is replaced by solving for *q*, referred to as the modal coordinates or modal participation factors.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Written in this form it can be seen that the vibration at each of the degrees of freedom is just a linear sum of the mode shapes.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] Furthermore, how much each mode "participates" in the final vibration is defined by q, its modal participation factor.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] An unrestrained multi-degree of freedom system experiences both rigid-body translation and/or rotation and vibration.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The existence of a rigid-body mode results in a zero natural frequency.
[src:predictive-maintenance-iiot/vibration-analysis] The corresponding mode shape is called the rigid-body mode.
